reviews.title: Easy Eggplant Parm!
reviews.review_text: The shoppers seem to have been taught; learning curve during Covid! Firm, shiny, no 'bruises'...you can cut out bruises too; dont trash whole eggplant. Crockpot dinner =Salt sliced unskinned eggplant on wood board, wipe after ten minutes (there's usually enough salt left on for flavor), put in layers; olive oil on bottom, canned tomato puree sauce, oregano, basil, eggplant, bread crumbs, grated cheese, garlic. Repeat until crok is full; final layer is sauce, garlic, spice, little more oil. We ad a bit of nut flour atop each layer of eggplant b4 breadcrumbs = added protein, thickens sauce. Cook in crock over night, add shredded mozzerella on bottom of each serving bowl/plate; heat will melt; over night, overcooks mozz, so wait! Taste and and sprinkle of salt if needed. A healthy eggplant parm; you'll have to wrk out how much spice to your taste. We were told about this and make weekly.

reviews.title: Yet another bad eggplant
reviews.review_text: I've ordered fresh eggplant on multiple occasions from WM and returned all but a couple of them for imperfections like dents, cuts, soft spots, etc. So I decided that I'd buy one in the store myself. The eggplant I selected was firm, the topnotch was green, with no exterior imperfections. Two days later I took it out of the fridge to cook and it had started to already get soft and the very green top was getting gray. The worst of this was the SMELL. Discovered that rotten eggplant smells as bad as rotten potatoes. Apparently it was rotting from the inside out and oozing out from under the the top like pus! Point is that in this case, if I'd ordered an eggplant for delivery and this one had been picked, the blame wouldn't be on the picker but the produce supplier. Either way, YUCK!
